1
00:00:15,104 --> 00:00:17,004
Where the hell is he, Stace?

2
00:00:17,217 --> 00:00:19,431
Don't worry, Mr. Lynch.
I'm sure he'll be here soon.

3
00:00:19,556 --> 00:00:22,730
This is ridiculous.
He goes on in less than five minutes.

4
00:00:28,677 --> 00:00:29,794
He's here.

5
00:00:29,919 --> 00:00:33,112
Get him up on stage
and I'll tell everybody he's on his way.

6
00:00:37,538 --> 00:00:38,538
Mr. Brava,

7
00:00:39,373 --> 00:00:40,581
We need to hurry.

8
00:00:41,570 --> 00:00:43,709
No advance copy of your speech
has been released.

9
00:00:43,877 --> 00:00:45,961
- Why the secrecy?
- Come hear it, and you'll know.

10
00:00:46,129 --> 00:00:48,724
Can you tell us anything
about what you're going to say?

11
00:00:49,784 --> 00:00:51,008
You want a sound bite?

12
00:00:51,479 --> 00:00:52,510
Fine.

13
00:00:52,678 --> 00:00:55,680
People who traffic in humans
are like cockroaches hiding in the dark.

14
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:59,044
- You have to expose 'em to the light.
- What do you mean?

15
00:00:59,893 --> 00:01:01,811
Will you be naming somebody?

16
00:01:05,732 --> 00:01:07,182
I'll be right back.

17
00:01:39,863 --> 00:01:41,363
We really have to...

18
00:01:47,557 --> 00:01:49,275
Help me! Somebody, please!

19
00:01:53,113 --> 00:01:55,119
Andy Burnside.
Kane county sheriff.

20
00:01:55,908 --> 00:01:58,804
Agent Teresa Lisbon.
This is Patrick Jane, our consultant.

21
00:02:00,102 --> 00:02:02,525
So the victim's name
was Hector Brava.

22
00:02:02,756 --> 00:02:05,056
He was a do-gooder.
Ran an organization

23
00:02:05,181 --> 00:02:07,277
called
the Sheltering Light foundation.

24
00:02:07,402 --> 00:02:09,211
They fight human trafficking.

25
00:02:09,636 --> 00:02:13,140
He was supposed
to give some kind of a speech.

26
00:02:15,150 --> 00:02:18,417
- So you're the psychic, huh?
- No. No such thing as psychics.

27
00:02:27,270 --> 00:02:29,791
Looks like cause of death
is blunt force trauma.

28
00:02:29,916 --> 00:02:31,275
Yeah, some of my men

29
00:02:31,443 --> 00:02:33,110
found a fire extinguisher
with blood.

30
00:02:33,278 --> 00:02:35,029
No, usable prints on it, though.

31
00:02:35,197 --> 00:02:37,364
What was he doing back here?

32
00:02:39,534 --> 00:02:40,534
This.

33
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:43,120
It's a text message.

34
00:02:44,289 --> 00:02:46,540
"Meet me through the staff door.
Carmen."

35
00:02:47,375 --> 00:02:50,461
- Tracking the sender now.
- How many Carmen have you ID'd?

36
00:02:50,974 --> 00:02:52,546
Two employees at the hotel,

37
00:02:52,714 --> 00:02:54,715
another two
were attending the conference.

38
00:02:55,164 --> 00:02:58,070
They all have alibis, though.
We're gonna keep looking.

39
00:02:58,470 --> 00:03:00,339
He had his wallet on him,
all credit cards,

40
00:03:00,464 --> 00:03:02,264
a lot of money,
so you can rule robbery out.

41
00:03:02,432 --> 00:03:04,099
Maybe.
Where's his speech?

42
00:03:05,686 --> 00:03:08,896
You said he was going to give a speech.
Wouldn't he have that speech

43
00:03:09,064 --> 00:03:10,264
on his person,

44
00:03:10,732 --> 00:03:12,650
or notes at least?
Did you find anything?

45
00:03:17,197 --> 00:03:19,532
- Find out everything about the speech.
- You got it.

46
00:03:23,887 --> 00:03:24,887
What?

47
00:03:26,823 --> 00:03:28,773
There's a contradiction here.

48
00:03:29,563 --> 00:03:31,836
The murder itself feels improvised.

49
00:03:32,004 --> 00:03:34,075
The fire extinguisher,
the semipublic location.

50
00:03:34,200 --> 00:03:35,500
But the setup...

51
00:03:36,039 --> 00:03:37,935
The text message was planned.

52
00:03:38,577 --> 00:03:40,227
No robbery to speak of.

53
00:03:41,195 --> 00:03:42,888
No assault other than the blow

54
00:03:43,056 --> 00:03:44,156
to the head.

55
00:03:44,641 --> 00:03:46,559
It doesn't feel like an anger killing.
But more

56
00:03:46,727 --> 00:03:48,577
like an act of desperation.

57
00:03:49,012 --> 00:03:51,291
The murderer wanted
to keep Brava from doing something

58
00:03:51,416 --> 00:03:52,523
or saying something.

59
00:03:53,115 --> 00:03:55,315
That's just what our psychic said.

60
00:03:56,153 --> 00:03:58,612
- Your psychic?
- Kristina Frye.

61
00:03:58,780 --> 00:03:59,822
You're kidding.

62
00:04:00,435 --> 00:04:01,907
What, you've heard of her?

63
00:04:05,662 --> 00:04:06,662
Relax.

64
00:04:07,784 --> 00:04:09,039
Don't force the memory.

65
00:04:09,377 --> 00:04:11,772
It'll come,
and the details will emerge.

66
00:04:12,183 --> 00:04:13,883
How much you paying her?

67
00:04:14,008 --> 00:04:15,796
- None of your business.
- That much?

68
00:04:15,964 --> 00:04:18,114
I'm working for the wrong people.

69
00:04:18,825 --> 00:04:20,092
Nice to see you again.

70
00:04:20,260 --> 00:04:21,260
You, too.

71
00:04:21,565 --> 00:04:22,636
Thank you.

72
00:04:22,892 --> 00:04:24,825
You got the sheriff
wrapped around your finger.

73
00:04:25,140 --> 00:04:26,932
He's a man with an admirably

74
00:04:27,100 --> 00:04:28,809
- open mind.
- He's also a man

75
00:04:28,977 --> 00:04:30,436
that likes to watch television

76
00:04:30,604 --> 00:04:33,814
with a cat curled up asleep on his lap
while his mother knits.

77
00:04:34,574 --> 00:04:36,775
But I'm sure
he'd prefer that to remain a secret.

78
00:04:38,952 --> 00:04:40,696
I thought you said
you weren't psychic.

79
00:04:40,942 --> 00:04:43,324
He is.
He's just not ready to accept it.

80
00:04:44,101 --> 00:04:46,535
Actually,
it was the cat hair on your pants,

81
00:04:46,703 --> 00:04:50,164
lack of wedding ring
and your general live-with-mom vibe.

82
00:04:51,038 --> 00:04:53,584
But if you want to believe
that his dead uncle Harry came down

83
00:04:53,752 --> 00:04:55,419
and whispered it in my ear,
be my guest

84
00:04:55,668 --> 00:04:57,379
Don't you get tired
of your cynicism?

85
00:04:57,702 --> 00:04:58,756
Weary as hell.

86
00:05:00,133 --> 00:05:01,717
What's the alternative?

87
00:05:02,050 --> 00:05:04,094
Why don't we give them
a little bit of time?

88
00:05:05,800 --> 00:05:07,654
Sorry about the mom thing.

89
00:05:08,966 --> 00:05:11,602
2x22
~ Red Letter ~

90
00:05:21,089 --> 00:05:22,257
I have a question.

91
00:05:22,382 --> 00:05:24,615
What are you doing
working with the cops?

92
00:05:24,783 --> 00:05:27,368
You were a spiritual psychoanalyst.
Did your patients catch on to you?

93
00:05:28,293 --> 00:05:31,205
I still have my practice.
Why, you looking for a therapist?

94
00:05:31,968 --> 00:05:33,668
Let me think about that.

95
00:05:35,018 --> 00:05:37,336
I heard that psychoanalysts
are a disease

96
00:05:37,504 --> 00:05:41,061
that present themselves as a cure.
And on top of that, you add in ghosts.

97
00:05:41,703 --> 00:05:44,343
Reflexive mockery,
a sign of a troubled soul.

98
00:05:44,645 --> 00:05:46,445
You got bored, didn't you?

99
00:05:46,859 --> 00:05:48,472
Got too easy taking their money.

100
00:05:50,343 --> 00:05:52,559
I think our gift obliges us
to help other people.

101
00:05:52,727 --> 00:05:53,895
Is that what you think?

102
00:05:54,020 --> 00:05:57,288
Our gift gives us an obligation to help.
I like that line. I'm gonna use it.

103
00:05:57,413 --> 00:05:59,493
Van pelt says there's a problem
tracing the message

104
00:05:59,618 --> 00:06:01,068
- that Brava got.
- What?

105
00:06:01,236 --> 00:06:03,127
The trail leads
to an electronic dead drop.

106
00:06:03,252 --> 00:06:05,906
No way to trace it back.
But she's keep looking,

107
00:06:06,074 --> 00:06:07,825
- run down those calls.
- And the speech?

108
00:06:07,993 --> 00:06:09,952
No word yet on
if he had it on him or not.

109
00:06:10,077 --> 00:06:12,204
But we haven't talked to the wife
She's inside.

110
00:06:13,103 --> 00:06:15,483
Hector and I knew something like
this might happen.

111
00:06:15,608 --> 00:06:17,960
He said there was too much at stake
to waste time worrying.

112
00:06:18,128 --> 00:06:19,586
What were you worried about?

113
00:06:19,754 --> 00:06:21,054
The traffickers.

114
00:06:22,007 --> 00:06:24,383
People who profit
from the enslavement of others.

115
00:06:24,551 --> 00:06:26,593
Hector was tireless
in his pursuit of them.

116
00:06:26,761 --> 00:06:29,408
Is there anyone you can think
of who may have wanted to kill him?

117
00:06:29,533 --> 00:06:32,558
My husband's received half a dozen
death threats since Christmas.

118
00:06:33,093 --> 00:06:34,643
If you're asking for names,

119
00:06:34,811 --> 00:06:36,645
we didn't make
a habit of filing the notes.

120
00:06:38,231 --> 00:06:40,733
He was gonna give a speech today.
Did he have it on him?

121
00:06:40,901 --> 00:06:42,303
Yes. Why?

122
00:06:42,819 --> 00:06:44,978
There was
some secrecy surrounding it.

123
00:06:45,238 --> 00:06:46,697
Do you know anything?

124
00:06:47,077 --> 00:06:48,227
No, I didn't.

125
00:06:52,954 --> 00:06:54,454
That wasn't unusual.

126
00:06:55,334 --> 00:06:57,584
Hector rarely shared the details
of his work with me.

127
00:06:57,709 --> 00:06:59,001
His way of protecting me.

128
00:07:01,277 --> 00:07:03,505
The person you need to talk to
is Russell Bigelow.

129
00:07:04,039 --> 00:07:05,674
He did research for Hector.

130
00:07:10,471 --> 00:07:12,306
You've been told
who I am and what I do?

131
00:07:15,455 --> 00:07:17,517
My communication
with the other side is like

132
00:07:17,979 --> 00:07:20,606
a long-distance phone call
with a bad connection.

133
00:07:20,774 --> 00:07:23,777
So often the messages I receive
are meaningless to me,

134
00:07:24,236 --> 00:07:27,072
but not to those with ones
who've passed over, okay?

135
00:07:27,729 --> 00:07:29,524
I'm really not big on this...

136
00:07:29,741 --> 00:07:32,201
- supernatural stuff.
- You're not alone.

137
00:07:37,701 --> 00:07:40,175
Your husband wants me
to remind you of something...

138
00:07:40,627 --> 00:07:42,410
that will make you smile...

139
00:07:42,963 --> 00:07:44,922
I'm getting an image of...

140
00:07:45,497 --> 00:07:46,673
Cherry blossoms?

141
00:07:48,385 --> 00:07:49,885
Does that mean anything to you?

142
00:07:53,723 --> 00:07:55,947
We were married under a cherry tree.

143
00:07:57,526 --> 00:07:58,811
How could you know that?

144
00:07:59,358 --> 00:08:01,507
He can recall foliage
from his wedding day,

145
00:08:01,632 --> 00:08:04,023
but he can't tell you
who killed him?

146
00:08:04,651 --> 00:08:07,038
Crossing over to the other side
can be confusing.

147
00:08:07,163 --> 00:08:08,971
It's a bit like waking up
from anesthesia.

148
00:08:09,096 --> 00:08:11,698
Sometimes it can take a while
to get real clarity.

149
00:08:13,874 --> 00:08:14,974
Makes sense.

150
00:08:16,955 --> 00:08:18,288
Carmen, mean anything to you?

151
00:08:19,608 --> 00:08:20,608
The opera.

152
00:08:21,021 --> 00:08:21,834
Why?

153
00:08:24,151 --> 00:08:25,351
That's pretty.

154
00:08:25,636 --> 00:08:26,636
My turn.

155
00:08:28,290 --> 00:08:30,050
Did your husband ever cheat on you?

156
00:08:30,591 --> 00:08:32,141
Did you cheat on him?

157
00:08:32,754 --> 00:08:33,846
Why?

158
00:08:34,117 --> 00:08:36,216
You're very noble and dignified.

159
00:08:36,341 --> 00:08:37,550
Very stoic.

160
00:08:38,206 --> 00:08:40,341
A Jackie o.
Thing going on there.

161
00:08:40,466 --> 00:08:43,021
Maybe you don't give a crap.
Maybe you're happy he's dead.

162
00:08:49,899 --> 00:08:50,899
Maybe not.

163
00:08:52,805 --> 00:08:53,949
I'd like you to leave.

164
00:08:54,601 --> 00:08:57,140
Good idea.
Jane, enough fun. Let's go.

165
00:09:01,034 --> 00:09:02,541
Thank you for the tea.
Very tasty.

166
00:09:06,558 --> 00:09:07,558
Nice work.

167
00:09:07,839 --> 00:09:10,039
She was hiding something.
I wanted to see what.

168
00:09:10,164 --> 00:09:11,483
What'd you learn?

169
00:09:11,608 --> 00:09:14,007
- It's early days.
- She's got a good arm.

170
00:09:14,132 --> 00:09:15,382
Did learn that.

171
00:09:15,781 --> 00:09:18,918
I'm not so sure this is such a good idea
I talk about this stuff.

172
00:09:19,279 --> 00:09:21,370
I'm just a researcher, you know?

173
00:09:22,084 --> 00:09:24,548
We understand that you're frightened,
but we really need

174
00:09:24,673 --> 00:09:27,149
- to know what was in that speech.
- You don't understand.

175
00:09:27,585 --> 00:09:29,900
Trafficking generates billions.

176
00:09:30,621 --> 00:09:32,487
There are governments
behind this stuff.

177
00:09:32,814 --> 00:09:35,574
It's like they can get to anybody.
Hector's death proves that.

178
00:09:35,742 --> 00:09:36,992
We can protect you.

179
00:09:38,119 --> 00:09:39,411
Only if you tell us.

180
00:09:41,251 --> 00:09:42,372
If you don't help us,

181
00:09:42,540 --> 00:09:44,833
then all the work that you've done
to stop these guys

182
00:09:45,145 --> 00:09:46,645
will be for nothing.

183
00:09:48,874 --> 00:09:50,124
Traffickers use

184
00:09:50,590 --> 00:09:53,388
quasi-legit businesses to launder
their money around the world.

185
00:09:54,189 --> 00:09:55,725
I watch audit trails.

186
00:09:56,165 --> 00:09:57,715
We made a connection.

187
00:09:58,818 --> 00:10:00,599
That's what's in Hector's speech.

188
00:10:00,767 --> 00:10:02,067
What connection?

189
00:10:03,866 --> 00:10:06,412
Have you ever heard of the world
anti-trafficking coalition?

190
00:10:06,715 --> 00:10:10,067
- One of the backers of the conference?
- A major charity.

191
00:10:10,306 --> 00:10:12,319
It's run by a guy
named Christopher Lynch.

192
00:10:12,686 --> 00:10:14,905
They assisted us in shutting down
a bunch of networks,

193
00:10:15,614 --> 00:10:17,407
but the trafficking continued.

194
00:10:18,484 --> 00:10:20,369
The money just went someplace else.

195
00:10:20,655 --> 00:10:22,496
It took a while to trace it,
but we found out

196
00:10:22,664 --> 00:10:25,374
the coalition is a front
for a trafficking group.

197
00:10:26,669 --> 00:10:27,793
They used us

198
00:10:27,961 --> 00:10:31,090
to shut down their own competition,
building themselves a monopoly.

199
00:10:32,737 --> 00:10:33,610
Here.

200
00:10:33,735 --> 00:10:35,716
- That the speech?
- My copy.

201
00:10:37,151 --> 00:10:39,008
Why didn't you
notify the authorities

202
00:10:39,133 --> 00:10:41,510
- once you found what was going on?
- 'cause hector said

203
00:10:41,635 --> 00:10:44,109
that he wanted to denounce
Lynch himself, in public.

204
00:10:44,714 --> 00:10:48,327
I said it was too dangerous,
but he just wouldn't listen.

205
00:10:49,657 --> 00:10:52,216
Did Brava ever mention
anybody named Carmen to you?

206
00:10:53,680 --> 00:10:55,000
No, not to me.

207
00:10:55,125 --> 00:10:55,946
Why?

208
00:10:56,188 --> 00:10:57,970
Bigelow is saying that the people

209
00:10:58,095 --> 00:11:00,233
fighting human trafficking
were traffickers.

210
00:11:00,358 --> 00:11:03,108
- Apparently.
- All right. You and Cho talk to Lynch.

211
00:11:03,233 --> 00:11:05,956
- See what he has to say.
- Okay, you got it.

212
00:11:09,694 --> 00:11:11,116
Are you guys joking?

213
00:11:11,463 --> 00:11:13,552
Because your humor's in bad taste.

214
00:11:13,923 --> 00:11:15,841
Hector was a colleague
and a good friend.

215
00:11:16,009 --> 00:11:18,297
Who was planning to give
a speech that would identify

216
00:11:18,422 --> 00:11:20,554
your coalition as a front
for human traffickers.

217
00:11:20,722 --> 00:11:22,475
He named you specifically.

218
00:11:23,384 --> 00:11:25,809
Someone is leading you down
the garden path, gentlemen.

219
00:11:26,599 --> 00:11:28,483
There's no basis of truth in this.

220
00:11:28,608 --> 00:11:30,731
You see that it's
in the traffickers' interest

221
00:11:30,899 --> 00:11:33,483
to split us up,
get us suspecting each other.

222
00:11:33,651 --> 00:11:36,129
- Brava went past suspecting you.
- Please.

223
00:11:36,254 --> 00:11:38,071
Hector saw conspiracies everywhere.

224
00:11:38,239 --> 00:11:40,586
- He liked being in the spotlight.
- We read the speech.

225
00:11:40,711 --> 00:11:44,538
- It makes a pretty convincing case.
- We're gonna clear this up right now.

226
00:11:44,774 --> 00:11:48,165
I will have my lawyers, give you access
to all our records, and you'll see

227
00:11:48,333 --> 00:11:50,208
that the coalition
has nothing to hide.

228
00:11:50,516 --> 00:11:53,003
Does the name "Carmen"
mean anything to you?

229
00:11:53,171 --> 00:11:55,627
Can you think of anybody
who'd want to kill Brava?

230
00:11:55,752 --> 00:11:57,852
Maybe only a few hundred people.

231
00:11:59,688 --> 00:12:00,888
Wait a second.

232
00:12:01,371 --> 00:12:02,262
One thing.

233
00:12:03,001 --> 00:12:04,747
Second night of the convention,

234
00:12:04,934 --> 00:12:08,040
I saw Hector having an argument
with a man named Tariq Sharif

235
00:12:08,353 --> 00:12:09,953
outside the hotel bar,

236
00:12:10,188 --> 00:12:13,398
and for my money,
the argument was about a woman.

237
00:12:13,566 --> 00:12:15,458
- How you'd tell?
- I know these guys,

238
00:12:15,583 --> 00:12:18,445
they definitely weren't having
a discussion about immigration policy.

239
00:12:20,088 --> 00:12:21,467
How's it coming with Lynch?

240
00:12:21,592 --> 00:12:24,076
Says a man called Tariq Sharif
was fighting with Brava.

241
00:12:24,244 --> 00:12:26,892
- Checking for an ID on Sharif.
- I took a look at the records

242
00:12:27,017 --> 00:12:29,089
that Lynch's lawyer emailed over.
First glance,

243
00:12:29,214 --> 00:12:31,176
couldn't find anything
on Brava's accusations.

244
00:12:31,301 --> 00:12:34,033
I checked Lynch's phone records.
He made a single call after we left

245
00:12:34,158 --> 00:12:35,796
to an anonymous disposable cell.

246
00:12:35,964 --> 00:12:37,797
- Origine?
- Here's the weird thing.

247
00:12:38,007 --> 00:12:40,214
It ends at a cell tower
in the middle of nowhere.

248
00:12:40,339 --> 00:12:41,720
- That is weird.
- Right?

249
00:12:41,845 --> 00:12:43,804
- We figured we'd go check it out.
- Okay.

250
00:12:44,148 --> 00:12:45,639
Here we go. I got him.

251
00:12:46,633 --> 00:12:47,974
Here's Tariq Sharif.

